# Lab Name
DOM XSS in jQuery selector sink using a hashchange event

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – DOM-Based XSS

## Objective
Exploit a DOM-based XSS vulnerability through a jQuery selector sink triggered by a hashchange event.

## Entry Point
URL Fragment (location.hash)

## Exploitation Type
DOM-Based XSS

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and inspect the page source

2. Observe that the application reads data from:

   location.hash

3. Notice that the value is passed into a jQuery selector sink

4. The selector is processed whenever a hashchange event occurs

5. Since the input is not properly sanitized, it is possible to inject malicious HTML containing an event handler

6. Craft a payload and place it in the URL fragment

7. Trigger the hashchange event by loading the page with the payload

8. Observe that the payload is processed by jQuery and JavaScript executes

## Payload Used

<iframe src="https://0a6200f60373655b80de1cb1005400d1.web-security-academy.net/"></iframe>

Exploit Server Payload:

<iframe onload="this.src+='#{<img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>}'"></iframe>

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript through a DOM-based XSS vulnerability triggered by a hashchange event.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- User account compromise
- Manipulation of page content

## Mitigation
- Avoid passing untrusted data into jQuery selectors
- Sanitize and validate data from location.hash
- Use safe DOM APIs instead of dynamic selectors
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Perform proper input validation and output encoding

## Learning
DOM-based XSS can occur when user-controlled data from location.hash is passed into jQuery selector functions without validation.
Applications should never trust URL fragments and must sanitize all client-side inputs before processing them.
